{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"db86423d-b38b-4401-8765-9df7bc3cb7ef","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe developer report confirms the bottleneck isn't compilation — it's the **cold-start overhead** of launching a new MSBuild process on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild loaded in-process.\n\nHere are three solutions, from simplest to most impactful:\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop (easiest win)\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nThis keeps the process alive and rebuilds on file changes — no repeated MSBuild startup cost.\n\n### 2. Enable MSBuild Server (.NET 8+)\nThe MSBuild Server keeps MSBuild nodes warm between CLI invocations, directly mirroring what VS does:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build   # first build is normal; subsequent builds reuse the server\n```\nAdd to your shell profile (`.bashrc`/`.zshrc`) for persistence.\n\n### 3. Ensure MSBuild node reuse is not disabled\nSome environments or CI scripts set this, which kills nodes after every build:\n```bash\n# Make sure this is NOT set to 1 in your dev environment:\nunset MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Benefit |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet watch build` | Eliminates startup cost entirely; file-watch driven |\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | Warm MSBuild nodes across separate `dotnet build` calls |\n| Node reuse not disabled | Ensures MSBuild can reuse background worker nodes |\n\n**Recommendation:** Use `dotnet watch build` during active development for the fastest edit→build cycle. For ad-hoc `dotnet build` calls, enable the MSBuild server. Together these bring CLI builds in line with VS performance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17b8ea81-7365-42e9-8ac6-b1adfbc33fa4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow (2-4 seconds) for incremental builds even when nothing changed, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've confirmed:\n- No analyzers slowing things down\n- Incremental build targets work correctly (targets do skip)\n- The project itself compiles in <500ms\n\nThe overhead is from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses an MSBuild server (a long-running process) that keeps the MSBuild nodes warm, avoiding the startup cost. The CLI equivalent is the **MSBuild Server** (also called \"build server\" or \"MSBuild daemon\"), which was introduced in .NET 8.\n\n\nThe main fix is to enable the MSBuild Server in .NET 8+, which keeps the build process alive between invocations—this is what Visual Studio does under the hood. By default it's enabled, but can be disabled with `DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` if needed.\n\nFor the fastest inner loop, I should use `dotnet watch` to keep the process running with incremental rebuilds, and the `-graph` flag enables static graph evaluation for multi-project builds, which can significantly speed things up. The graph-based build approach can optimize multi-project builds by parallelizing independent projects, which complements the other strategies. Now I should focus on giving the user concrete, actionable recommendations they can implement immediately.","outputTokens":1268},"id":"a3b89df4-4f47-46e2-bced-38d8357e346c","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:50:48.252Z","parentId":"56e38bad-e171-41aa-b5d6-4e8e97dd0c60"}
